<h1 align="center">Protein Structure Analysis</h1>
<h2 align="center">Heat Shock Proteins</h2>
<p align="center">Heat shock proteins are highly conserved and
present in all organisms. Zi, L. &amp; Srivastava, P., Heat Shock
Proteins, Curr Protoc Immunol. (Feb. 2004). Selected heat shock
proteins, also known as chaperones, are involved in protein
folding and unfolding, assembly of protein complexes, transport
and sorting of proteins into the correct cellular compartments,
cell-cycle control and signaling, and protection of cells against
stress and apoptosis. See Id. The four proteins selected have
pairwise sequence identity less than 50%, are all less than 300
residues, and have images taken using x-ray crystallography with a
resolution greater than 1.9, and are all small heat shock proteins
(sHSPs). Sun, Y. &amp; MacRae, T.H., Small Heat Shock Proteins:
molecular and chaperone function. Cell Mol. Life Sci., pp. 2460-76
(Nov. 2005). As heat shock proteins, they associate with nuclei,
cytoskeleton, and membranes, and as molecular chaperones they bind
partially denatured proteins. See Id.<br>
</p>

<div align="center"><b>Each of the proteins show significant alpha
helices, random coils, and extended strands. 'Alpha helices are
more robust to mutations than beta strands.' Abrusan G. &amp;
Marsh J., PLOS Computational Biology (December 9, 2016).&nbsp;
We see a significant presence of alpha helices in all 4
proteins. Moreover, we also see a significant presence of
extended strands. Let's look at another multiple sequence
alignment, but this time on which shows consensus secondary
structure information.<br>
<br>
<img
src="data:image/png;base64,"
alt=""><br>
</b><font size="-1">Multiple sequence alignment completed using:
PROMALS3D: a tool for multiple sequence and structure alignment.
Jimin Pei, Bong-Hyun Kim and Nick V. Grishin. Nucleic Acids Res.
2008 36(7):2295-2300.<br>
Available at: http://prodata.swmed.edu/promals3d/promals3d.php</font><br>
<b> <br>
</b>
<h3><b>This shows a significant presence of beta strands, and an
alpha helix in the first alignment (beta strands are denoted
as "e" and alpha helices as "h"). This is consistent with the
secondary structure analysis above, which shows a significant
presence of extended strands. </b></h3>

<h3><br>
</h3>
<h3>We see the alpha-crystallin domain in all proteins except HSP
40. We also see the CS domain in HSP 20.1 and the DnaJ C
terminal domain in HSP 40. The CS domain overlaps with the
homologous HSP-20 like chaperone superfamily. CS Domain
(IPR007052), EMBL-EBI, Wellcome Genome Campus, Hixton,
Cambridgeshire, UK, available at:
http://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/entry/IPR007052. Likewise, the
DnaJ C terminal domain is also associated with the chaperone
family.</h3>

<h3>Correlation between structural similarity and percent sequence
identity for multiple sequence/structure alignments of whole
proteins. As shown, we see a linear positive correlation between
structural similarity (as measure by RMSD) and percent sequence
identity. <br>
</h3>
<p><img
src="data:image/png;base64,"
alt=""><br>
</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h3>Correlation between structural similarity and percent sequence
identity for multiple sequence/structure alignments of protein
fragments. As shown, we do not find the correlations which exist
above. This is because the upper threshold of sequence identity
values are very close to the structural similarity scores,
hence, the cluster of points (roughly) between 70 and 90 (on the
x-axis) and the cluster around 20. It should be noted that the
fragments were generated by a pairwise sequence alignment
algorithm, and thus we would not necessarily expect to find
correlations.&nbsp; Moreover, we could expect a similar lack of
correlation if we were to use the motif or secondary structure
sequence data for our plots. The reason is quite simple, we see
many of the same domains and secondary structure profiles in all
four of the small heat shock proteins under investigation,
suggesting an evolutionary relationship and a similar clustering
of the data that we see in the plot shown below.<br>
